                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d866">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 865.857An2/36</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Austria-Hungary</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PFC1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Penfield</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vienna</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-11-23T20:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 23, 1915, 8 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received November 24, 7 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>991. On the 19th sent note Minister for Foreign Affairs on subject <hi
                        rend="italic">Ancona</hi> in sense requested by you, with strong personal
                    letter to <persName corresp="#p_BVRS1">Burian</persName>. Receiving no reply
                    have to-day had long conference with him. <persName corresp="#p_BVRS1"
                        >Burian</persName> assures me has ordered full report from marine Section
                    and when received will place it in my hands immediately. Expect report in day or
                    two. Rest assured am doing all possible to hasten matter. Consensus of opinion
                    here is that submarine was German-built but technically now Austrian. Cattaro
                    believed to be operating base. <persName corresp="#p_BVRS1">Burian</persName>
                    said he was positive <hi rend="italic">Ancona</hi> did not halt when commanded
                    to do so, and that most people were lost through condition of panic incident to
                    Latin blood. Official Austro-Hungarian list 1914–15 gives twelve (<hi
                        rend="italic">U–1</hi> to <hi rend="italic">12</hi>); first six in
                    commission at outbreak of war, maximum length 43 meters, no guns. <hi
                        rend="italic">U–7</hi> to <hi rend="italic">12</hi> then building Kiel,
                    length 70 meters, mounting quick-firers, caliber not given. <hi rend="italic"
                        >U–12</hi> officially reported sunk by Italians August 13 last.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PFC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Penfield</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
